A '''certificate of public convenience and necessity''' or '''certificate of public convenience''' is a type of [[regulatory compliance]] certification for [[public service]] industries. [[Private companies]] wishing to provide essential public services in certain countries must be granted a CPCN before constructing facilities and offering services.
==Philippines== In the Philippines, a certificate of public convenience (CPC) is required for private provision of public services for which no franchise, either municipal or legislative, is required by law, such as a [[common carrier]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.batasnatin.com/law-library/mercantile-law/transportation-laws/2218-certificate-of-public-convenience-cpc.html|title=What is a Certificate of Public Convenience (CPC)?|work= Philippine Law Library}}</ref>
==United States== The first [[U.S. state]] statutes for certificate of public convenience (CPCN) were issued in 1870, and the [[U.S. Congress]] included a certification provision in [[U.S. federal law]] in the [[Transportation Act of 1920]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.jstor.org/discover/1121802?sid=21105515254613&uid=2&uid=4|title=Origins of the Certificate of Public Convenience and Necessity: Developments in the States, 1870 - 1920|last=Jones|first=William K.|journal=[[Columbia Law Review]]|volume=79|number=3|pages=426–516|doi=10.2307/1121802}}</ref> Examples of industries requiring a CPCN from a U.S. state include the provision of [[telecommunications]] in [[New York (state)|New York]] state,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.dps.ny.gov/W/PSCWeb.nsf/All/C78F4BE884AA2FA885257687006F3964?OpenDocument|title=CPCN: Certificate of Public Convenience and Necessity|publisher=[[New York State Public Service Commission]]|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref> transportation of [[natural gas]] in [[Alaska]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/15/720a|title=15 U.S. Code § 720a - Issuance of certificate of public convenience and necessity|work=[[Legal Information Institute]]|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref> and a range of public services in [[Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/ilcs/fulltext.asp?DocName=022000050K8-406|title= Illinois Compiled Statutes: Sec. 8-406. Certificate of public convenience and necessity|work=[[Illinois General Assembly]]|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref>
